# Samba User Management

## Step 1: Ensure system user exists
# (use your main Pi user, e.g., `pi`, or create a dedicated NAS user)
```bash
sudo adduser nasuser
Step 2: Set Samba password for the user
This is separate from the system password
bash
Copy code
sudo smbpasswd -a nasuser
Enable the user for Samba access
bash
Copy code
sudo smbpasswd -e nasuser
Step 3: Verify Samba user list
bash
Copy code
sudo pdbedit -L
Output example:
pi:1000:Pi User
nasuser:1001:NAS User
yaml
Copy code

---

## Step 4: (Optional) Create dedicated folders per user
```bash
mkdir -p /mnt/nas/nasuser
sudo chown -R nasuser:nasuser /mnt/nas/nasuser
Notes
System users â‰  Samba users.

A Samba user must exist in both system (/etc/passwd) and Samba (smbpasswd).

Samba user password may differ from system password.

